                        <div id="agenda-intro">
                          <h2>Introduction to Agenda</h2>
                          <div class="divide20"></div>
                          <h3>Agenda</h3>
                          <p>Freeze Date: 15th May, 1947</p>
                          <p>The history of conflict in the Palestine area has lasted longer than the United Nations itself. For Centuries, the two hostile groups (Israel and Palestine) have been embroiled in territorial disputes over holy cities, such as Jerusalem, that carry great symbolic meaning for both Jewish Israelis and Muslim Arabs.</p>
                          <p>The Special Committee on Palestine was established to conduct investigations into the proposed solutions to resolve problems in Palestine. The United Kingdom which originally brought the issue to the notice of the General Assembly for arbitration, occupied the territory in 1918. Its administration was formalised by the League of Nations under the Palestine mandate with the prerogative to carry out the Balfour Declaration to establish “in Palestine, a national home for the Jewish People, it being clearly understood that nothing should be done which might prejudice the civil and religious rights of existing non-Jewish communities in Palestine”. Despite the best intentions of the original mandate, conflict between Jews and Arabs grows each year and it is the United Nations Special Committee on Palestine’s duty to find a solution that will effectively restore peace.</p>
                          <p>As a commission of the United Nations, UNSCOP’s main function is to draft resolutions which recommend to the parties involved proposals which will, to the best of the committee’s knowledge, guarantee peaceful the resolution of the conflict. In addition, the committee may request and consider reports pertinent to the topic of discussion but cannot establish an independent body to do so.</p>
